## 💡 Design Decisions (Answers to Your Questions)

### 1. Chatbot + Frequency-Based Calming Audio

When the AI chatbot detects crisis/mood keywords, it will:

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    A[Student types message] --> B{Keyword Detection}
    B -->|anxiety/panic| C[🎵 Play 432Hz + Breathing Guide]
    B -->|sadness/lonely| D[🎵 Play 528Hz Healing Frequency]
    B -->|anger/frustration| E[🎵 Play Delta Wave 2Hz Binaural]
    B -->|severe crisis| F[🚨 Auto-Refer to Counsellor]
    F --> G[📧 Email + 💬 WhatsApp + 🔔 Dashboard Alert]
    C --> H[Show coping strategies]
    D --> H
    E --> H
```

**Frequencies mapped to moods:**
| Mood Detected | Frequency | Type | Effect |
|--------------|-----------|------|--------|
| Anxiety / Panic | 432 Hz | Solfeggio | Calming, reduces heart rate |
| Sadness / Loneliness | 528 Hz | Solfeggio | "Love frequency", emotional healing |
| Anger / Frustration | 2 Hz Delta | Binaural Beat | Deep relaxation |
| Stress / Overwhelm | 10 Hz Alpha | Binaural Beat | Relaxed focus |
| Insomnia | 3 Hz Delta | Binaural Beat | Sleep induction |

Audio files will be generated using the **Web Audio API** (no external files needed — pure sine wave generation in the browser).

---

### 2. Professional Referral → Email + WhatsApp + Dashboard

When chatbot detects severe crisis keywords (e.g., "suicide", "self-harm", "can't go on"):

| Channel | Technology | Implementation |
|---------|-----------|----------------|
| **Dashboard** | MongoDB + Socket-like polling | Referral saved to DB, counsellor sees it in real-time on dashboard |
| **Email** | Nodemailer + Gmail SMTP | Auto-sends email to counsellor with student ID (anonymized) + crisis summary |
| **WhatsApp** | Twilio WhatsApp API | Sends WhatsApp message to counsellor's registered number |

> [!NOTE]
> For demo/interview: Email will work with a Gmail app password. WhatsApp will use Twilio's free sandbox (no paid account needed for testing).

---

### 3. Why Keep Peer Volunteers? Why NO Peer Chat?

**Why 1-on-1 chat is Student ↔ Counsellor ONLY (not Student ↔ Volunteer):**

| Reason | Explanation |
|--------|-------------|
| **Liability** | Volunteers are untrained students — giving private advice could be harmful and creates legal liability for the institution |
| **Ethics** | Private mental health conversations require professional training; volunteers could unintentionally say something damaging |
| **Safety** | Forum is public/moderated = built-in safety net. Private chat has no oversight |
| **Scope** | Volunteers should handle community support, not clinical intervention |

**Why Peer Volunteers are still valuable:**

| Value | How |
|-------|-----|
| **Reduce counsellor burden** | Volunteers handle forum moderation so counsellors focus on 1-on-1 sessions |
| **Early detection** | Volunteers spot concerning forum posts and escalate to counsellors before crisis |
| **Community building** | Trained volunteers write empathetic public replies in the forum, making students feel heard |
| **Scalability** | 2-3 counsellors can't monitor a forum with 500+ students; 20 trained volunteers can |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Peer Volunteers moderate the **public forum only** and escalate concerning cases. All private/clinical communication is strictly **Student ↔ Counsellor**.

